                <tr> <!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="title" --> 
                  <td align="left" valign="top" class="maintitle"><strong>Studying 
                    Sociology</strong></td>
                  <!-- InstanceEndEditable --></tr>
                <tr> 
                  <td align="left" valign="top" class="bodytext">&nbsp; </td>
                </tr>
                <tr> <!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="main text" --> 
                  <td align="left" valign="top" class="bodytext"> <p>Sociology 
                      is constantly being renewed and re-developed. With rapid 
                      social change occurring, locally and globally, which affect 
                      individuals, social groups and other social units we face 
                      a continuous challenge to deepen out sociological understanding. 
                      Processes of critique and review are as much a part of sociology 
                      as they are of other academic disciplines. You can expect, 
                      therefore to be introduced to new concepts and theories 
                      as well as classical approaches to understanding the social 
                      world. </p>
                    <p>We can 
                      easily identify major social changes through reflection 
                      on experiences in each of our lives. As examples, we could 
                      refer to the UK, where there have been major economic changes 
                      as the international or global dimensions of capitalism 
                      have continued to have structural consequences; and to South 
                      Africa, where the ending of the regime of Apartheid is recent. 
                      We can also be alerted to social change by comparing our 
                      own expectations with regard to work and family lives with 
                      those of our parents and grandparents. You will not be surprised 
                      to know, given this context, that our sociology curriculum 
                      at Trinity and All Saints is therefore also undergoing constant 
                      revision. Do not be surprised if we consult you about further 
                      changes to the degree scheme while you are a student here.                      </p>
                    <p>We aim 
                      to provide a good understanding of the core of sociology 
                      and to give opportunities for individual study by covering 
                      four major aspects of the field: </p>
                    <p>(i) 
                      sociological theory <br>
                      (ii) strategies and methods of sociological research <br>
                      (iii) study and comparison of different societies <br>
                      (iv) study of particular areas of sociology. </p>
                    <p>We also 
                      aim, through your education in sociology, to foster the 
                      development of transferable skills, i.e. useful skills which 
                      you can deploy effectively in other contexts.These 
                      include: </p>
                    <p><i>reasoning 
                      skills:</i> use of concepts; critical ability; analysis 
                      and evaluation of arguments, synthesis of perspectives; 
                      identifying and questioning assumptions; arguing a case; 
                      problem solving and decision making; </p>
                    <p><i>skills 
                      of numeracy and graphicacy:</i> evaluation of assumptions 
                      of measurement; assessment of the constructions and limitations 
                      of data; statistical summary and inference; graphical representation 
                      and awareness of distortion </p>
                    <p><i>information 
                      technology skills:</i> use of computer networks, data construction 
                      and management; skills with computer packages, use of data 
                      bases, CD-ROM and the world-wide web </p>
                    <p><i>communication 
                      skills:</i> clarity, relevance structure and form in written 
                      and oral presentations </p>
                    <p><i>reflexivity:</i> 
                      dealing with assumptions, issues and questions in written 
                      and other forms of representation </p>
                    <p><i>group-work 
                      skills:</i> ability to work with others in groups and to 
                      jointly prepare materials. </p>
                    <p>By the 
                      end of the sociology course as a whole, our objectives are 
                      that you will be able to: <br>
                      (i) analyse, interpret and evaluate sociological arguments<br>
                      (ii) 
                      design, undertake and report on social research <br>
                      (iii) deploy a range of skills derived from sociological 
                      study <br>
                      (iv) work co-operatively with others in diverse social contexts.                      </p>
                    <p>The 
                      structure of the sociology degree scheme is as follows:                      </p>
                    <p><span class="headers"><b>Level 
                      1</b></span>                      <br>
                      <i>Core:</i> <br>
                      Introduction to UK Society = 20 credits <br>
                      Introduction to Social Theory and Research = 20 credits 
                      <br>
                      <i>Options:</i> <br>
                      Race, Ethnicity and Community = 20 credits <br>
                      Identities and Communications =20 credits </p>
                    <p><span class="headers"><b>Level 
                      2</b></span><br>
                      <i>Core:</i> 
                      <br>
                      Understanding and Explanation in Sociology <br>
                      <i>Core Preference:</i> <br>
                      North American Societies: USA and Canada <br>
                      Developing Societies: Brazil and South Africa <br>
                      <i>Options:</i> <br>
                      Debates and Issues in Social Policy <br>
                      Feminist Writers and their Social Context <br>
                      Modern Ideologies <br>
                      Sociology of Work and Employment </p>
                    <p><span class="headers"><b>Level 
                      3</b></span> 
                      <br>
                      <i>Core: </i><br>
                      Contemporary Sociological Theory <br>
                      Social Research: Strategy and Design <br>
                      <i>Core preference (1 or 2 of) </i><br>
                      Sociology of Crime and Control <br>
                      Sociology of Education <br>
                      Sociology of Religion <br>
                      Politics and Society <br>
                      Debates and Issues in Gender Studies</p>
            <br> 
